Meteorite Landing Analysis¶

This project analyzes data regarding mass, location, and composition of meteorite landings using a dataset titled "Meteorite_Landing.csv". The dataset used in this project was sourced from kaggle.com.

In [197]:
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
sns.histplot(df['year'], bins=20, kde=True)
plt.title('Distribution of Meteorite Falls by Year')
plt.xlabel('Year')
plt.ylabel('Count')
plt.show()

The histogram of meteorite falls over time reveals a dramatic shift in recorded discoveries.

For most of the dataset's history — spanning over a thousand years — the number of recorded meteorites per year remained relatively low.

However, beginning in the late 20th century and especially around the year 2000, there is an exponential spike. One particular year near 2000 records over 60,000 meteorites — a massive outlier compared to previous centuries.

This spike is likely not indicative of an actual increase in meteorite activity, but rather reflects a data reporting phenomenon. Possible explanations include:

  • Advances in technology and data collection methods (e.g. satellite imagery, digital recordkeeping).

  • Increased public and scientific interest in cataloging meteorites.

  • The digitization and consolidation of older meteorite finds into modern databases, possibly grouped under more recent "discovery" or entry dates.

This pattern highlights the importance of distinguishing between the fall date of meteorites versus the recording date, and how modern recordkeeping has influenced the apparent volume of data in recent years.

In [198]:
correlation_matrix = df[['mass (g)', 'year', 'reclat', 'reclong']].corr()

plt.figure(figsize=(8, 6))
sns.heatmap(correlation_matrix, annot=True, cmap='coolwarm')
plt.title('Correlation Matrix')
plt.show()

The correlation matrix reveals the strength and direction of linear relationships between the numerical variables in the meteorite dataset. Here's a breakdown of key insights:

  • 🔴 The diagonal red line of 1s represents perfect self-correlation, where each variable is compared to itself — a standard feature in any correlation matrix.

  • 🌍 Latitude (reclat) and longitude (reclong) show a very weak negative correlation (-0.54), indicating essentially no linear relationship between the two — expected since they are independent geographic coordinates.

  • 📅 Year and reclat have a moderate negative correlation (-0.23), suggesting that more recent discoveries are less likely to be in the same latitude range as older ones. This may reflect shifts in discovery locations due to technological advances or changes in exploration patterns.

  • 🪨 Year and mass are also negatively correlated (-0.12), implying that more recent meteorite discoveries tend to have lower masses. This might be due to improved detection methods identifying smaller fragments that previously would have gone unnoticed.

  • 📌 Longitude (reclong) and year show a weak positive correlation (0.20), potentially indicating a geographic trend in discovery regions over time.

  • 🪨 Mass has very weak correlations with all other variables (reclat: 0.036, reclong: -0.027), suggesting that the mass of a meteorite is largely independent of where or when it was discovered.

Overall, the heatmap suggests there are no strong linear relationships between most variables.

In [199]:
# Group by fall status and get average mass
mass_by_fall = df.groupby('fall')['mass (g)'].mean()

mass_by_fall.plot(kind='bar', figsize=(8, 6))
plt.title('Average Mass by Fall Status')
plt.ylabel('Average Mass (g)')
plt.show()

This visualization compares the average mass of meteorites based on their fall status — whether the meteorite was "Fell" (observed as it fell) or "Found" (discovered later).

  • 💥 Meteorites that were observed falling ("Fell") have a significantly higher average mass of around 50,000 grams.

  • 🔍 Meteorites that were "Found" without a witnessed fall have a lower average mass, at approximately 20,000 grams.

This difference may suggest that larger meteorites are more likely to be noticed as they fall, due to their visibility, noise, or resulting impact. In contrast, smaller meteorites might go unnoticed during descent and are only discovered later, often by chance or through targeted searches.

The pattern highlights how observation bias plays a role in meteorite data — size influences detectability, and this impacts how meteorites are classified and recorded.

The bar chart showing the count of meteorites by century highlights a striking increase in recorded meteorite discoveries over time:

  • The 20th century (1901–2000) shows the highest number of discoveries, with over 20,000 recorded meteorites.

  • The 21st century (2001–2013 in this dataset) follows, with approximately 7,500 meteorites — still a very high count considering the shorter time frame.

  • The 19th century (1801–1900) shows a dramatic drop-off.

  • Earlier centuries have either very few or no recorded meteorites — likely due to the lack of formal tracking, scientific recording methods, or public awareness during those periods.

This trend likely reflects the rise of modern science and recordkeeping, improvements in detection technologies, and global coordination in reporting meteorite finds. It’s a strong indicator that discovery count is more about data availability and human activity than actual meteorite fall frequency.

The 16th century shows an unusually high average meteorite mass due to the presence of a few exceptionally large meteorites. These outliers significantly skew the overall average mass, making it appear much larger than what would be expected based on the majority of data.

Key outliers driving this spike include:

  • Campo del Cielo (1575): A meteorite with an enormous mass of 50,000,000 grams (50 metric tons) — by far the largest meteorite in the dataset.

  • Morito (1600): A massive meteorite weighing 10,100,000 grams (10.1 metric tons).

  • Castrovillari (1583): A much smaller, but still large meteorite at 15,000 grams (15 kg).

Interestingly, despite the Hoba meteorite weighing a massive 60 tons (a weight that's larger than Campo del Cielo), the 20th century bar for average mass is much smaller than the 16th century. This discrepancy could be due to the fact that meteorite discovery and recording became more systematic in the 20th century, leading to a much higher volume of smaller meteorites that lowers the overall average mass. On the other hand, the 16th century dataset contains fewer, but significantly larger meteorites that skew the average.

This highlights the importance of examining individual data points when interpreting summary statistics, as outliers can distort the overall trends. Without the extreme outliers, the mass distribution in the 16th century would likely resemble more typical values seen in the 19th and 20th centuries.

# Remove zero and missing mass values
filtered_df = df[df['mass (g)'] > 0]

# Apply log transformation for better scaling of the large values
filtered_df['log_mass'] = filtered_df['mass (g)'].apply(lambda x: np.log(x) if x > 0 else 0)

plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))

sns.boxplot(x='century', y='log_mass', data=filtered_df)
plt.title('Log Distribution of Meteorite Masses by Century (After Filtering Zero and Missing Values)')
plt.xlabel('Century')
plt.ylabel('Log(Mass) (g)')
plt.show()

fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(12, 6))

century_avg_mass = filtered_df.groupby('century')['log_mass'].mean()

sns.barplot(x=century_avg_mass.index, y=century_avg_mass.values)
plt.title('Average Log-Mass of Meteorites by Century')
plt.xlabel('Century')
plt.ylabel('Average Log(Mass) (g)')
plt.show()

The analysis of meteorite mass distribution by century reveals interesting trends, especially when we consider the impact of extreme outliers and missing or zero values in the original data.

Original Distribution of Meteorite Mass by Century:¶

In the original distribution, several centuries show significant outliers that skew the interpretation of the data. The 16th century stands out with a large mass range (up to several tons). The 20th century, despite having large meteorites like Hoba, displays a much smaller mass range, likely due to the larger number of smaller meteorites recorded during that time. The distribution for centuries like the 18th, 19th, and 21st centuries shows small or sparse data, with many outliers significantly affecting the overall mass range.

Log-Transformed Distribution of Meteorite Mass by Century:¶

To better understand the true distribution of meteorite masses and reduce the influence of extreme values, I applied a logarithmic transformation to the mass data. This transformation helped normalize the mass distribution and make it easier to spot patterns in the data.

After filtering out zero values and missing data, the transformed distribution shows a clearer picture:

  • The 16th century still has a concentration of larger meteorites, but the impact of extreme values is now less pronounced, allowing us to see more clearly how other meteorites from the same century compare.

  • The 20th century now shows a more concentrated range of meteorite masses, without being dominated by a few extreme values.

  • The outliers are more easily identifiable, making it clear that certain centuries (like the 16th) have a high concentration of massive meteorites, but they do not dominate the entire dataset.

This transformation provides a better view of the underlying trends and allows us to focus on general trends in meteorite mass, without the distortion caused by extreme outliers and missing values.

# Calculate standard deviation of mass for each classification
common_stdev = df[df["recclass"].isin(common_meteorite_df["Classification"])] \
    .groupby("recclass")["mass (g)"].std().reset_index(name="mass_std")

uncommon_stdev = df[df["recclass"].isin(uncommon_meteorite_df["Classification"])] \
    .groupby("recclass")["mass (g)"].std().reset_index(name="mass_std")

# Merge std dev into existing dataframes
common_meteorite_df = common_meteorite_df.merge(common_stdev, left_on="Classification", right_on="recclass", how="left").drop(columns=["recclass"])

The mass standard deviation (spread) among the top 10 most common meteorite classifications reveals significant differences in how consistent their masses are:

  • H5 meteorites have the highest variability in mass, with a standard deviation of approximately 60,000 grams, suggesting a wide range of sizes within this classification.

  • L5 follows with a spread around 50,000 grams, indicating similarly high variation.

  • L6 shows a notable drop to around 20,000 grams, suggesting a more consistent mass range compared to H5 and L5.

  • The remaining classifications—including H6, H4, H4/5, LL5, LL6, L4, and CM2—cluster closely together with standard deviations between 7,000 and 15,000 grams, indicating relatively stable mass ranges.

These findings suggest that while some classifications like H5 and L5 span a broad spectrum of sizes, others have more tightly grouped masses. This could be related to differences in composition, frequency of recovery, or fragmentation during atmospheric entry.

    wordcloud = WordCloud(
        width=800, height=400,

        stopwords=None,  
        collocations=False
    ).generate(text_data)

Summary of Meteorite Data Analysis¶

  1. Data Cleaning and Preprocessing:

The dataset was cleaned by removing rows with missing or zero values in critical columns such as mass and GeoLocation. Years that were too far in the future or from centuries that had no recorded meteorite falls were filtered out. This ensured that the analysis focused on reliable and relevant data.

  1. Distribution of Meteorite Falls:

The distribution of meteorite falls by year revealed a significant spike around 2000, with a sharp increase in the number of meteorites recorded around 2000–2010. Before this period, the number of falls was significantly lower, indicating either fewer meteorites were recorded or discovered.

The distribution of meteorite mass by century showed the largest meteorites discovered in the 16th century, with a significant drop in the size of meteorites from the 17th century onward. The 20th century had outliers, such as the Hoba meteorite, which weighs around 60 tons.

Century buckets revealed the concentration of meteorite falls in the 20th and 21st centuries, with very few falls from prior centuries, reinforcing the trend of modern meteorite discovery.

  1. Average Mass and Outliers:

The average mass of meteorites varied significantly between centuries, with the 16th century showing the largest meteorites. However, many meteorites in the 20th and 21st centuries were notably smaller, despite some outliers, such as the Hoba meteorite.

The distribution of meteorite masses indicated that while there were outliers, the majority of meteorites weighed far less than the largest recorded masses.

  1. Correlation Analysis:

The correlation matrix showed weak to moderate correlations between features. Notably, there was little correlation between the reclat, reclong, and mass columns, suggesting that meteorite size may not necessarily influence where meteorites are found geographically.

A negative correlation between reclat and year suggested that older meteorites were more likely to be found at lower latitudes, though this correlation is weak.

  1. Meteorite Classifications:

The most common classifications by meteorite type were L6, H5, and H4 (chondrites), which dominated the dataset. These types are typically composed of silicate minerals, with distinct chemical compositions.

There were at least ten least common meteorite classifications including Mesosiderite-C, H/L3.9, and Martian (chassignite), which showed far fewer records, possibly due to their rare occurrence or discovery.

  1. Standard Deviation and Spread:

The standard deviation of meteorite masses for the common classifications was higher, indicating that while common meteorites had a larger range of masses, they still tended to fall within a specific mass range. In contrast, the least common meteorites showed far more variability in terms of mass, suggesting they were less predictable in size.

Key Takeaways:¶

Meteorite discovery peaked in the 20th and 21st centuries, reflecting technological advancements and more focused meteorite searches.

Meteorites from the 16th century were often much larger than those found in modern times, with significant outliers like the Campo del Cielo meteorite influencing mass distributions.

Meteorite classification plays a key role in understanding meteorite composition and provides insights into their origins and structure. The most common classifications were silicate-based chondrites, while rarer classifications were more exotic in composition.

The analysis showed that geographic location and mass have little correlation, suggesting that meteorite size is not a primary factor in determining fall locations.

The distribution of meteorite masses and their spread across centuries indicates that meteorite falls have become more consistent in the last few centuries.
